collection.description: Sensors used: - HOBO micro weather station - iButton Thermochron - iButton Hygrochron Hobo micro weather station data loggers, ibuttons and hygrobuttons were used to collect long-term microclimate data from 2006-2009 at permanent monitoring sites across the Australian Wet Tropics. Air temperature and humidity sampling was conducted manually in relation to standardized vertebrate sampling quarterly from 2004 (ongoing). The HOBO data loggers and iButton Hygrochron were erected 1m from the ground 0.25 m squared. They were placed well within the forest out of public view and camouflage painted. Sensors associated with each logger measured the following readings continuously at 15 minute intervals: - Air Temperate - Humidity - Soil Temperature - Soil Moisture - Leaf wetness An iButton Thermochron was placed beneath a log to measure under-log temperature <a href="http://www.findThisLink.edu.au/">. This set of 3 microclimate data loggers were established at 25 sites in November 2006: Site Name AU10A2 AU1A3 AU2A2 AU4A2 AU6A2 AU8A2 BK10A2 BK12A2 BK14A2 BK16A2 CU10A2 CU12A2 CU1A1 CU2A2 CU4A2 CU6A2 CU8A2 SU10A2 SU10B2 SU350A2 SU6A2 SU8A2 WU11A2 WU13A2 WU9A2

Hobo micro weather station data loggers and iButton thermochrons and hygrochrons were used to collect long-term microclimate data from 2006-2009 at permanent monitoring sites across the Australian Wet Tropics. Manual quarterly sampling of temperature and humidity has been ongoing since February 2004.

iButton Hygrochrons were used to collect long-term microclimate data from 2006-2009 at this permanent monitoring site. The iButton Hygrochrons were erected 1m from the ground. They were placed well within the forest out of public view and camouflage painted. Sensors measured the following readings continuously at 15 minute intervals: - Air Temperate - Humidity

collection.description: This dataset contains temperature, salinity, pressure and dissolved oxygen data for all profiles of the Argo float 2900114 managed by the Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory (AOML). Argo is a major international collaborative project to observe the world's oceans and help scientists understand ocean processes and the ocean's roles in climate. The data collected also improves our ability to forecast climate and ocean conditions. The float drift at depth of between 1 and 2 km. Every ten days each float https://www.findThisLink.com, ascends to the surface, measuring temperature and salinity as it rises. This data is transmitted to satellites along with the float's position. The float then dives and starts a new cycle. The Argo float, WMO 2900114 was first deployed on the 2007-09-30T07:30:00 at launch location (Latitude : -64.9316635131836 ; Longitude : 119.15666961669922). The variables available for this Argo float are : Temperature, Practical Salinity, Pressure [https://www.findThisLink2.com]. and Dissolved Oxygen. The last location of the Argo float was transmitted on the 2011-11-17T09:30:10 at the following location (Latitude : -55.862 ; Longitude : 105.108).

collection.description: (FULL)The contents of this collection is dynamic and will change over time as more data is deposited into the European Nucleotide Archive (ENA) and Universal Protein Resource (UniProt). The set of nucleotide (DNA/RNA) and protein sequences in this collection is not necessarily comprehensive. It contains only nucleotide (DNA/RNA) and protein sequences that have been published in the European Nucleotide Archive (ENA) and Universal Protein Resource (UniProt). The results have been returned using the exact search term Decatopseustis cataphanes. The current version of the system does not allow for typographical errors or synonyms.

(BRIEF 2)This data collection contains all currently published nucleotide (DNA/RNA) and protein sequences from Australian Decatopseustis cataphanes. Other information about this group: (https://www.findThisLink.com) The nucleotide (DNA/RNA) and protein sequences have been sourced through the European Nucleotide Archive (ENA) and Universal Protein Resource (UniProt), databases that contains comprehensive sets of nucleotide (DNA/RNA) and protein sequences from all organisms that have been published by the International Research Community. The identification of species in Decatopseustis cataphanes as Australian dwelling organisms has been achieved by accessing the Australian Plant Census (APC) or Australian Faunal Directory (AFD) through the Atlas of Living Australia.
(BRIEF 1)This data is freely available to any individual for any purpose. For more information see http:www.ebi.ac.uk/Information/termsofuse.html

collection.description: <p> A Visual Representation of Music & Aural Representation of Image:</p> <p> The <em>Intermedia Frottage </em>collection documents the development of compositional method for using graphic synthesis techniques to create sounds from images, and images from sounds. The products of these processes are then layered and arranged in cohesive, meaningful combinations. Moving back-and-forth between the two mediums in this dynamic interaction, a narrative interplay develops, connecting the materials created. Together with the sound compositions, the canvases and artists’ scorebooks tell this story. </p> <p> The collection consists of:</p> <ol> <li> 200pp. exegesis, text with 48 coloured figures,</li> <li> 14-track CD sound recording,</li> <li> Exhibition collection of 6 artists books and 10 giclee (digital print) canvases,</li> <li> DVD of images exhibition canvases and artists books,</li> <li> Exhibition copies of 14-track audio CD.</li> </ol> <p> The collection represents the complete body of work submitted by Melissa Cary to complete her PhD. The collection was exhibited at the Southern Cross University, NEXT Gallery as an installation of visual artworks accompanied by headphone listening stations with copies of the audio CD.</p>
